Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:00 PM Prosecuting attorney Alexander Huber in court for the State of Wisconsin. Defendant Sufian N. Manya in court, in custody. Clerk N. Nobile.
MINUTES: Discussion held on status of case. DE states he and his family are trying to retain new counsel since his prior attorney withdrew. Court will adjourn to allow the DE to hire another attorney.
Status conference scheduled for November 17, 2022 at 02:30 pm.
Letter re: rotation for DE returned by USPS.Not deliverable as addressed. Unable to forward.
Notice of assignment of judge returned. Return to sender. Not deliverable as addressed. Unable to forward.

10:01 AM  State appears by Attorney Alexandra Smathers. Defendant, Sufian N. Manya, appeared with Attorney Phil Marry who appears on behalf of Attorney Fadil K Idrizi.  Clerk N. Nobile.
MINUTES: Attorney Marry states that Attorney Idrizi was just retained and is requesting an adjournment so he may meet with the DE request/review the discovery. The State does not object. Court adjourns.  Final pre-trial scheduled for October 3, 2022 at 02:00 pm.

09:50 AM
Defendant Sufian N. Manya appeared by phone means and in-custody.
Prosecuting Atty Zachary L Brost appeared for State of Wisconsin.  Court Reporter:  Kimberly Keel.  Clerk:  JM.
MINUTES:
